      SEC v. ESG
   =20
 =20
We talked yesterday about a US Securities and Exchange Commission enforceme=
nt case against BNY Mellon Investment Adviser Inc. The issue is that BNY Me=
llon ran some mutual funds and advertised that they considered environmenta=
l, social and governance factors in all of their investment decisions, but =
in fact they only considered those factors in like 75% of their investment =
decisions, so BNY Mellon had to pay the SEC a $1.5 million fine.=C2=A0That =
is a simple and objectively measurable problem: BNY Mellon=E2=80=99s market=
ing materials said things like =E2=80=9Cahead of investing, each security b=
eing considered for investment by our global industry analysts must have an=
 ESG quality review,=E2=80=9D and BNY Mellon in fact did ESG quality review=
s that produced ESG scores before making most of its investments, but somet=
imes it did not. Sometimes it bought stocks with no ESG scores at all.=C2=
=A0What I suggested yesterday is that this might be all that the SEC can do=
 with its enforcement powers to fight =E2=80=9Cgreenwashing,=E2=80=9D the w=
orry that=C2=A0asset managers talk about their focus on ESG investing but a=
re in some way not =E2=80=9Creally=E2=80=9D doing ESG. This was=C2=A0true o=
f BNY Mellon in a trivial way: It claimed to do ESG reviews and sometimes d=
id not. But presumably in=C2=A0most=C2=A0cases, the people concerned about =
greenwashing are not concerned about=C2=A0that. They are concerned about in=
vestment managers who say =E2=80=9Cwe do ESG reviews of every investment,=
=E2=80=9D and=C2=A0do=C2=A0in fact do ESG reviews of every investment, but =
the reviews are bad. For whatever reason: They are too lazy, or they focus =
on the wrong sorts of ESG, or they give companies credit for stuff that you=
 think is bad and penalize them for stuff that you think is good. What is =
=E2=80=9Creal=E2=80=9D ESG is to some degree subjective, and there will alw=
ays be critics of how any fund approaches it. And=C2=A0that, I argued, is h=
arder for the SEC to police: There are no rules for what is =E2=80=9Creal=
=E2=80=9D ESG, so investment managers get to decide for themselves, and as =
long as those decisions are not in obvious bad faith the SEC can=E2=80=99t=
=C2=A0and probably shouldn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0go after them.Well but the other =
alternative is for the SEC to write some rules on what =E2=80=9Creal=E2=80=
=9D ESG is:Rules being prepared by the Securities and Exchange Commission w=
ould specify disclosures to be made by investment funds that have terms suc=
h as =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9Csustainable=E2=80=9D, or =E2=80=9Clow-=
carbon=E2=80=9D in their names. The rules are expected to require informati=
on about how ESG funds are marketed, how ESG is incorporated into investing=
 and how these funds vote at companies=E2=80=99 annual meetings, according =
to people familiar with the SEC=E2=80=99s thinking. =E2=80=A6=E2=80=9CThere=
 is currently a wide range of what asset managers might mean by certain ter=
ms and what criteria they might use,=E2=80=9D Gary Gensler, SEC chair, said=
 in March. =E2=80=9CIt is easy to tell if milk is fat free. It might be tim=
e to make it easier to tell whether a fund is really what they say they are=
.=E2=80=9DThe four-member SEC, which includes Gensler and two other Democra=
tic appointees, is scheduled to vote on Wednesday to release the draft rule=
s for public comment.You could imagine a rule that says =E2=80=9Cyou can=E2=
=80=99t call yourself an ESG fund unless you vote in favor of all sharehold=
er proposals asking companies to write reports about their carbon impact.=
=E2=80=9D The actual rule wouldn=E2=80=99t say that; it would say, like, =
=E2=80=9Cif you vote against a shareholder proposal about carbon reports, y=
ou need to disclose that, possibly in a parenthesis in your fund name,=E2=
=80=9D like =E2=80=9CThe BlackRock Large-Cap ESG Fund (But We Voted Against=
 17 Climate Resolutions Last Year)=E2=80=9D[5] or whatever. The SEC is prim=
arily a disclosure regulator, but it knows how to make disclosure of things=
 it dislikes=C2=A0unpleasant, so that everyone chooses not to do those=C2=
=A0things to avoid disclosing them.[6]I think there are obvious potential p=
roblems with the SEC deciding what is and is not ESG. =E2=80=9CIt is easy t=
o tell if milk is fat free=E2=80=9D because=C2=A0you measure to see how muc=
h fat is in it. It is harder to tell if a fund is ESG because different peo=
ple have different environmental, social and governance priorities. A rule =
that helps investors understand whether an =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D fund share=
s their ESG priorities is probably helpful. A=C2=A0rule that mandates that =
ESG funds pursue the SEC=E2=80=99s ESG priorities =E2=80=94=C2=A0that says =
what sorts of things are and aren=E2=80=99t ESG =E2=80=94=C2=A0is trickier.=
=C2=A0I expect the SEC=E2=80=99s rules will do a bit of both.=C2=A0
