What is the right way to think about the diffusion of the famously weird cu=
lture of Bridgewater Associates, the world=E2=80=99s largest hedge fund? Br=
idgewater founder Ray Dalio has spent a lot of time in recent years=C2=A0ma=
rketing=C2=A0that culture, with a book and a YouTube video with Diddy=C2=A0=
and a lot of publicity about how his principles for business management can=
 work beyond Bridgewater.Is that, like, just the usual thing where a guy ge=
ts rich managing a hedge fund and then wants to turn his wealth into=C2=A0r=
espect, in this case by becoming a business/life guru?Are there commercial =
advantages to Bridgewater from the guru thing? If you are a big pension fun=
d and you allocate a lot of money to Bridgewater and you constantly read ar=
ticles about how weird its=C2=A0culture is, maybe you withdraw your money. =
If you constantly read articles about how=C2=A0good its culture is, and wat=
ch videos of=C2=A0Ray Dalio mentoring Diddy, maybe you give Bridgewater mor=
e money.Are there commercial disadvantages? What if Bridgewater=E2=80=99s e=
dge comes from (1) having a truth-centered meritocratic culture,=C2=A0(2) a=
ttracting truth-centered people with lots of merit, and (3) being the=C2=A0=
only=C2=A0place those people fit in? What if Dalio is so successful at prom=
oting his management philosophy that dozens of big companies convert to a B=
ridgewater-like culture, and smart ambitious people who love truth have lot=
s of good options and stop going to Bridgewater? What if other investment f=
irms convert to Bridgewater=E2=80=99s culture, get better at finding the tr=
uth, and compete away Bridgewater=E2=80=99s returns?Anyway any time I read =
about the Dot Collector I am going to laugh, cringe, and mention it in Mone=
y Stuff:Coinbase, a cryptocurrency trading firm that garnered attention for=
 banning salary negotiations and political speech among employees in recent=
 years, is testing another practice that has raised eyebrows internally: as=
king employees to frequently rate each other. Some employees at the company=
 have been using a real-time evaluation app invented by Bridgewater Associa=
tes, the well-known hedge fund founded by Ray Dalio, which helped enforce a=
 culture of =E2=80=9Cradical transparency=E2=80=9D that encourages blunt ho=
nesty, according to two people with direct knowledge.The app, Dot Collector=
, is sold by Principles, a company Dalio founded. Coinbase=E2=80=99s versio=
n lets employees evaluate co-workers, including their managers, on how well=
 they exemplify the crypto firm=E2=80=99s 10 cultural tenets=E2=80=94which =
include clear communication, efficient execution and positive energy=E2=80=
=94during meetings and other interactions, these people said. After an inte=
raction, an employee can give their colleague a thumbs-up, thumbs-down, or =
neutral rating. =E2=80=A6While rapid-feedback technology is becoming more c=
ommon in the tech industry, it=E2=80=99s rare for tech companies to use the=
 Dot Collector software itself, said Paul Rubenstein, chief people officer =
of the employee analytics provider Visier.=E2=80=9CI have never actually ta=
lked to some other head of HR who uses it,=E2=80=9D he said.After you read =
this column I guess let me know on Twitter how well it exemplifies Money St=
uff=E2=80=99s 10 cultural tenets. Honestly I should probably write a list o=
f Money Stuff=E2=80=99s 10 cultural tenets. Making fun of crypto, saying th=
at everything is securities fraud, addressing convoluted insider-trading hy=
potheticals=C2=A0=E2=80=A6=C2=A0I am going to stop because I find this emba=
rrassing; clear-eyed critical self-knowledge is not for me. But it=E2=80=99=
s nice that Coinbase is into it.
