</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a=C2=A0trade that you could do=
:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16p=
x 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Sell a one-year total return swa=
p on $100 million of=C2=A0Stock X=C2=A0to a hedge fund. The idea of the swa=
p is=C2=A0that you give the hedge fund economic exposure to $100 million of=
 Stock X. Simplifying slightly, (1) if Stock X goes up Y% over the year, yo=
u pay the hedge fund $Y million at the end of the year; (2) if Stock X goes=
 down Z% over the year, the hedge fund pays you $Z million at the end of th=
e year; and (3) the hedge fund pays you interest =E2=80=94=C2=A0say $4 mill=
ion, 4% of the $100 million notional amount =E2=80=94=C2=A0during the year.=
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Go out into the money market and =
borrow $100 million at, say, 3% interest.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom=
: 5px;">Use the money you borrowed in Step 2 to buy $100 million worth of S=
tock X to perfectly hedge the swap in Step 1. If Stock X goes up Y% over th=
e year, you make $Y million from your stock position and pay the hedge fund=
 $Y million on the swap, perfectly offsetting each other.</li></ol><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a very popular and normal trade. You are getti=
ng paid an interest-rate margin: You pay 3% to borrow $100 million, you eff=
ectively=C2=A0lend it to the hedge fund at 4%, and you collect the $1 milli=
on difference as profit. The stock is almost=C2=A0irrelevant=C2=A0to you.=
=C2=A0 The hedge fund wants it to go up, but you don=E2=80=99t care. This i=
s a fixed-income trade; you are getting paid the difference between two int=
erest rates.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What are you getting paid for?=
 Well, for one thing, you are taking credit risk to the hedge fund: If the =
stock goes down and the hedge fund doesn=E2=80=99t pay, you lose money. (Th=
e stock isn=E2=80=99t <em>entirely=C2=A0</em>irrelevant to you, since this =
credit risk only matters if the stock goes down.)=C2=A0For another thing, y=
ou are getting paid for providing funding: You went out to the money market=
 to borrow that $100 million on the hedge fund=E2=80=99s behalf, and the fu=
nd is rewarding you for that effort.[1]=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">Ordinarily the person doing this trade =E2=80=94=C2=A0the =E2=80=9Cyou=
=E2=80=9D in this description =E2=80=94=C2=A0is a big investment bank. Ther=
e are many reasons for that. Banks have lots of money, and easy access to m=
oney markets to borrow more. They can buy stock easily. They talk to all th=
e hedge funds and have trading agreements with them and hold themselves out=
 as market makers, so when a hedge fund wants to do a swap like this it wil=
l naturally call one of its banks and not, say, some other hedge fund.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/27823461.265613/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlua=
W9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMDUvYmlsbC1od2FuZy1zLWFyY2hlZ29zLXN3YXAtYWZ0ZXJt=
YXRoLWlzLWF3a3dhcmQtZm9yLWJhbmtzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MjQyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9=
tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDUyNCZ1dG1fY2=
FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8323dcb3" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">a trade=
</a> that was made <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/27823461.265613/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLz=
IwMjEtMDctMjkvYXJjaGVnb3Mtd2FzLXRvby1idXN5LWZvci1tYXJnaW4tY2FsbHM_Y21waWQ9Q=
kJEMDUyNDIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0=
ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNTI0JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cB4a92c99b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;">infamous</a> recently by the <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27823461.265613/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21=
iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtMjcvYmlsbC1od2FuZy1hcnJlc3QtaW=
5zaWRlLXRoZS12aWNpb3VzLWN5Y2xlLW9mLWFyY2hlZ29zLWNvbGxhcHNlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1M=
jQyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0=
bV90ZXJtPTIyMDUyNCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B17c21824" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">blowup</a> at Archegos Capital Management, which did a b=
unch of giant swaps with a bunch of banks on about a dozen stocks. When som=
e of the stocks went down, it turned out Archegos wasn=E2=80=99t good for t=
he money; the banks sold the stocks to limit their losses and a couple of t=
hem lost a lot of money. This is the credit risk that I mentioned above,=C2=
=A0everyone is aware of it, banks try to manage it carefully =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0<em>most=C2=A0</em>of Archegos=E2=80=99s banks were fine! =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0and charge an appropriate spread for it, and bank regulators also try to=
 keep an eye on it.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is another proble=
m for the bank, though. The problem for the bank is that, if you do this tr=
ade, you will add $100 million of assets (the stock you buy in Step 3) and =
$100 million of liabilities (the money you borrow in Step 2) to your balanc=
e sheet. If you are a bank, growing your balance sheet costs you money. Cla=
ssically a bank has to have <em>capital</em> in proportion to its assets; i=
f a bank has $100 million of assets, regulators might require it to=C2=A0ha=
ve at least $8 million of equity capital =E2=80=94=C2=A0stockholders=E2=80=
=99 money =E2=80=94=C2=A0to cushion it against losses. (The actual number i=
s way more complicated than that but 8% is sort of a crude generic capital =
ratio.) In my hypothetical trade, the bank just borrowed $100 million to fu=
nd its $100 million of stock, but in reality the bank would need to fund so=
me of it with equity. Bankers tend to think that equity is expensive. If yo=
ur shareholders expect a 15% return on equity, and this trade increases you=
r capital requirements by $8 million, then the capital =E2=80=9Ccost=E2=80=
=9D of this trade is about $1.2 million a year =E2=80=94=C2=A0more than you=
 are actually getting paid.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Incidentally yo=
u also have the=C2=A0<em>swap </em>on your balance sheet, as an asset or a =
liability, but a small one. Derivatives go on your balance sheet at their f=
air value, and the fair value of this swap, initially, is roughly zero: It =
is roughly a fair bet between you and the hedge fund, so its expected value=
 is close to zero.[2] As the stock moves the swap=C2=A0will become a bigger=
 asset (if the stock goes down) or liability (if it goes up), but initially=
 it does not have that much balance-sheet impact.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">What you might want, if you are a clever banker, is to move that $10=
0 million of stock=C2=A0off your balance sheet. Your thought process might =
be:</p><ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px=
 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Look, in Step 2 of this trade, yo=
u were borrowing $100 million from the money market for 3%.</li>=09<li styl=
e=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">So there are people in the world =E2=80=94=C2=A0m=
oney-market funds, pensions, whoever =E2=80=94=C2=A0who have $100 million a=
nd are willing to lend it to you=C2=A0for 3% interest so you can buy the st=
ock to do this trade.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">What if, ins=
tead of lending you the money, those people=C2=A0<em>bought the stock for y=
ou.=C2=A0</em></li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They would spend th=
eir $100 million on Stock X, and put it in a box, and write you a total ret=
urn swap on it, one that exactly offsets the swap you write to the hedge fu=
nd in Step 1.[3]</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">And you would pay=
 them a financing rate of, say, 3.1% on the swap, which is more than they w=
ere getting in the money market.</li></ul><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now,=
 instead of borrowing money to buy stock, you =E2=80=94=C2=A0the bank =E2=
=80=94 just sit in between two swaps. Instead of growing your balance sheet=
 by $100 million, you don=E2=80=99t do that. Instead of making 1% on this t=
rade (4% financing rate from the hedge fund minus 3% cost of money), you ar=
e making 0.9% (4% on one swap minus 3.1% on the other), but you are freeing=
 up $100 million of balance sheet so it=E2=80=99s worth it. You=E2=80=99re =
better off because you save on capital. The lenders are better off because =
you=E2=80=99re paying them an extra 0.1%. The hedge fund is indifferent; it=
=E2=80=99s still getting the same swap from you. Everyone is better off!</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Arguably=C2=A0<em>the financial system=C2=A0<=
/em>is worse off because you have lower capital requirements against essent=
ially identical risks, but, you know, that's how capital regulation works.=
=C2=A0If regulation requires $10 of capital for a trade, and $7 of capital =
for an economically identical trade that uses different paperwork, then mon=
ey will naturally flow to the trade with lower capital requirements. If tha=
t leads to levels of bank capital that are too low overall, or if it encour=
ages banks to pile into very risky trades, then that=E2=80=99s bad.=C2=A0</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/27823461.265613/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnR=
pY2xlcy90aGUtYWlyYm5iLW9mLXdhbGwtc3RyZWV0LXdhbnRzLXRvLWZyZWUtdXAtdHJhcHBlZC=
1iYW5rLWNhcGl0YWwtMTE2NTMyNTY1NzY_bW9kPWl0cF93c2omcnU9eWFob28/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB11797bb2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">a Wall Street Journal story about Capitolis I=
nc.</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the same way Airbnb=
 turned vacant homes into vacation rentals, Capitolis is turning the unused=
 capital of investing giants like BlackRock Inc. into assets that banks can=
 use to facilitate all kinds of transactions. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">Enter Capitolis: It matches investments from asset managers, pension=
 funds and money-market funds with the transactions banks facilitate and un=
derwrite. The firm has raised some $60 billion from investors for the banks=
 to use in the past two years and reduced trillions of dollars in trading p=
ositions, said Gil Mandelzis, its founder and chief executive.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co. and Citigroup Inc., two of th=
e biggest players in global markets, use Capitolis to free up their traders=
 to work with more clients. The two banks are also Capitolis investors, alo=
ngside venture-capital firms Sequoia Capital and Andreessen Horowitz. A Mar=
ch funding round valued the startup at $1.6 billion.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Mr. Mandelzis=E2=80=99s new idea resembles an old one: Bank=
s have long sliced up and sold their big corporate loans to other banks and=
 investors. Capitolis figured out how to use this syndication concept to tu=
rn all kinds of banking products=E2=80=94foreign-exchange swaps and lines o=
f credit, to name a few=E2=80=94into a kind of fixed-income security or loa=
n they can sell to investors.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For exa=
mple, Citigroup owns a basket of equities tied to its clients=E2=80=99 trad=
es. Capitolis, using investor money, essentially mirrors Citigroup=E2=80=99=
s trades=E2=80=94entering into a derivative contract to take the risk off t=
he bank=E2=80=99s balance sheet. Citigroup is freed up to do more trading, =
and the investors get a fixed payout.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s what I described=C2=A0above. Instead of Citi b=
uying stocks to offset its clients=E2=80=99 total return swaps (the first t=
rade I described above), an off-balance-sheet Capitolis vehicle buys the st=
ocks and writes total return swaps to Citi, lowering Citi=E2=80=99s=C2=A0ca=
pital requirements. Here is an <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/27823461.265613/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc3BnbG9iYWwuY29tL19hc3NldHMvZG=
9jdW1lbnRzL3JhdGluZ3MvcmVzZWFyY2gvMTEyODIyNTYucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B602f975e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">S&amp;P Global Ratings report</a> about one of these veh=
icles, called Ionic Capital II Trust, which can raise up to $15.5 billion t=
o buy stocks to hedge Citigroup total return swaps. The vehicle issues comm=
ercial paper with an A-1 rating. Basically if you are BlackRock or whoever,=
 and you are looking to park some money somewhere safe for a short period, =
you can lend your money to Citi directly (which grows Citi=E2=80=99s balanc=
e sheet), or you can lend your money to this thing, which will buy stocks f=
or Citi without growing its balance sheet. Your credit risk is pretty much =
the same (you are relying on Citi paying you), but this thing is better for=
 Citi=E2=80=99s capital treatment.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Jour=
nal story goes on[4]:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Capitolis=
=E2=80=99s plan to outsource banks=E2=80=99 capital needs, while still in i=
ts infancy, has the potential to reshape their role in the market and the b=
roader economy. Divorcing the capital required for transactions from the pr=
ocess of executing them could allow banks to serve more customers=E2=80=94b=
usinesses and consumers alike=E2=80=94without taking on so much risk that t=
hey could blow up the financial system. The goal, the company=E2=80=99s fou=
nders say, is a market better able to absorb big spikes in trading volume a=
nd loan demand.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWhen it=E2=
=80=99s all over, we will have uncoupled capital from the underwriting equa=
tion,=E2=80=9D said Mr. Mandelzis. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re going to look bac=
k and wonder how they used to do it when it was bundled.=E2=80=9D</p></bloc=
kquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is: In the ordinary course, banks =
do trades that require them to buy stuff, and then they have the stuff on t=
heir balance sheets. In a perfect world (for the banks!), banks would do tr=
ades that require them to buy stuff, but the stuff would all be in separate=
ly funded special-purpose vehicles for capital efficiency.</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">I am telling you about this because I think it is smart and=
 neat and, as a former structurer of financial boxes and arrows, I apprecia=
te some good boxes and arrows. I also think that, as stories like =E2=80=9C=
banks are doing derivatives trades and then putting them into off-balance-s=
heet vehicles to reduce capital requirements=E2=80=9D go, this one is quite=
 benign. I think the next financial crisis is unlikely to be caused by off-=
balance-sheet funding of equity total return swaps. But certainly I realize=
 that not everyone will take it that way! I realize that Archegos is pretty=
 recent! Some people simply do not like stories like =E2=80=9Cbanks are doi=
ng derivatives trades and then putting them into off-balance-sheet vehicles=
 to reduce capital requirements,=E2=80=9D no matter how good they are.</p><=
