<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">SEC v. ESG</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/27823461.265613/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMjMvdGhlLXNlYy1nb2VzLWFmdGVyLWdyZWVud2FzaGlu=
Zz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTI0MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U=
9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA1MjQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB478fc65f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">talked yesterday</a> about a US Securi=
ties and Exchange Commission enforcement case against BNY Mellon Investment=
 Adviser Inc. The issue is that BNY Mellon ran some mutual funds and advert=
ised that they considered environmental, social and governance factors in a=
ll of their investment decisions, but in fact they only considered those fa=
ctors in like 75% of their investment decisions, so BNY Mellon had to pay t=
he SEC a $1.5 million fine.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is a=
 simple and objectively measurable problem: BNY Mellon=E2=80=99s marketing =
materials said things like =E2=80=9Cahead of investing, each security being=
 considered for investment by our global industry analysts must have an ESG=
 quality review,=E2=80=9D and BNY Mellon in fact did ESG quality reviews th=
at produced ESG scores before making most of its investments, but sometimes=
 it did not. Sometimes it bought stocks with no ESG scores at all.=C2=A0</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What I suggested yesterday is that this might=
 be all that the SEC can do with its enforcement powers to fight =E2=80=9Cg=
reenwashing,=E2=80=9D the worry that=C2=A0asset managers talk about their f=
ocus on ESG investing but are in some way not =E2=80=9Creally=E2=80=9D doin=
g ESG. This was=C2=A0true of BNY Mellon in a trivial way: It claimed to do =
ESG reviews and sometimes did not. But presumably in=C2=A0<em>most=C2=A0</e=
m>cases, the people concerned about greenwashing are not concerned about=C2=
=A0<em>that</em>. They are concerned about investment managers who say =E2=
=80=9Cwe do ESG reviews of every investment,=E2=80=9D and=C2=A0<em>do</em>=
=C2=A0in fact do ESG reviews of every investment, but the reviews are bad. =
For whatever reason: They are too lazy, or they focus on the wrong sorts of=
 ESG, or they give companies credit for stuff that you think is bad and pen=
alize them for stuff that you think is good. What is =E2=80=9Creal=E2=80=9D=
 ESG is to some degree subjective, and there will always be critics of how =
any fund approaches it. And=C2=A0<em>that</em>, I argued, is harder for the=
 SEC to police: There are no rules for what is =E2=80=9Creal=E2=80=9D ESG, =
so investment managers get to decide for themselves, and as long as those d=
ecisions are not in obvious bad faith the SEC can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>and pr=
obably shouldn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>go after them.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">Well but the other alternative is for the SEC to <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27823461.265613/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY=
29tL2NvbnRlbnQvNmZlZmRiMmMtZjcyZS00ZTUyLWI5NWItYzA3MjdhZWIxYTk0/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cB158e887f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">write some rules on what =E2=80=9Creal=E2=
=80=9D ESG is</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Rules being =
prepared by the Securities and Exchange Commission would specify disclosure=
s to be made by investment funds that have terms such as =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=
=9D, =E2=80=9Csustainable=E2=80=9D, or =E2=80=9Clow-carbon=E2=80=9D in thei=
r names. The rules are expected to require information about how ESG funds =
are marketed, how ESG is incorporated into investing and how these funds vo=
te at companies=E2=80=99 annual meetings, according to people familiar with=
 the SEC=E2=80=99s thinking. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=
=80=9CThere is currently a wide range of what asset managers might mean by =
certain terms and what criteria they might use,=E2=80=9D Gary Gensler, SEC =
chair, said in March. =E2=80=9CIt is easy to tell if milk is fat free. It m=
ight be time to make it easier to tell whether a fund is really what they s=
ay they are.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The four-member SEC, =
which includes Gensler and two other Democratic appointees, is scheduled to=
 vote on Wednesday to release the draft rules for public comment.</p></bloc=
kquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could imagine a rule that says =E2=
=80=9Cyou can=E2=80=99t call yourself an ESG fund unless you vote in favor =
of all shareholder proposals asking companies to write reports about their =
carbon impact.=E2=80=9D The actual rule wouldn=E2=80=99t say that; it would=
 say, like, =E2=80=9Cif you vote against a shareholder proposal about carbo=
n reports, you need to disclose that, possibly in a parenthesis in your fun=
d name,=E2=80=9D like =E2=80=9CThe BlackRock Large-Cap ESG Fund (But We Vot=
ed Against 17 Climate Resolutions Last Year)=E2=80=9D[5] or whatever. The S=
EC is primarily a disclosure regulator, but it knows how to make disclosure=
 of things it dislikes=C2=A0unpleasant, so that everyone chooses not to do =
those=C2=A0things to avoid disclosing them.[6]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">I think there are obvious potential problems with the SEC deciding what=
 is and is not ESG. =E2=80=9CIt is easy to tell if milk is fat free=E2=80=
=9D because=C2=A0<em>you measure to see how much fat is in it</em>. It is h=
arder to tell if a fund is ESG because <em>different people have different =
environmental, social and governance priorities</em>. A rule that helps inv=
estors understand whether an =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D fund shares their ESG pr=
iorities is probably helpful. A=C2=A0rule that mandates that ESG funds purs=
ue the SEC=E2=80=99s ESG priorities =E2=80=94=C2=A0that says what sorts of =
things are and aren=E2=80=99t ESG =E2=80=94=C2=A0is trickier.=C2=A0I expect=
 the SEC=E2=80=99s rules will do a bit of both.=C2=A0</p><table class=3D"li=
